sudo adduser alice (password: 123) 
	everything else default
sudo adduser bob (password: 123)
	everything else default
cat /etc/passwd => check if user created or not
sudo groupadd devteam => create new group
adding users to devteam group:
	sudo usermod -aG devteam alice
	sudo usermod -aG devteam bob
cat /etc/group => check group
create project in /srv (public srv directory):
	mkdir /srv/project
give group access to project and also give rwx permissions:
	sudo chown :devteam /srv/project
	sudo chmod 770 /srv/project
switch to alice:
	su - alice
	edit bashrc:
		nano ~/.bashrc
			add alias gotoproj='cd /srv/project'
		source ~/.bashrc (reload bash)
		gotoproj (check if command works)
switch to bob:
	su - bob
	edit bashrc:
		nano ~/.bashrc
			add alias gotoproj='cd /srv/project'
		source ~/.bashrc (reload bash)
		gotoproj (check if command works)
switch back to alice:
	gotoproj
	touch alice_notes.txt (Create new file)
	nano alice_notes.txt (add dummytext and save file)
switch to bob:
	gotoproj
	ls (view files to see if alice_notes.txt is visible)
	cat alice_notes.txt (check to see if text can be viewed)
	nano alice_notes.txt (try and edit, if permission denied then bob currently doesnot have permission meaning no user other than alice can edit the file, need to give permissions to all group members to be able to edit file)			
switch back to admin (zain in this case):
	su - zain
	sudo chmod g+s /srv/project (all new files inherit devteam group, now everyone in devteam group should have access to new files)
to test new access switch to bob:
	su - bob
	gotoproj (go to /srv/project)
	touch bobfile.txt (create new file)
	nano bobfile.txt (add dummytext and save)
switch to alice:
	su - alice
	gotoproj (go to /srv/project)
	ls (see if files are visible)
	cat bobfile.txt (check if text can be viewed)
	nano bobfile.txt (edit to see if permissions are working)

This exercise allows us to practice:
	- managing users
	- managing groups
	- creating/managing permissions
	- adding aliases
	- troubleshooting access issues
